{TEXT -1 36 "d. y-intercept of the function = 128" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 61 "e. For large positive and
 large negative x, f 4 tends to + \241\304" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Pol
ynomials:  Local extreme values and monotonicity.  Beyond information \+
of the type gathered above about intercepts and signs of a polynomial,
  other important information can be determined from the so called \"c
ritical points\" of a polynomial.  The critical points of a polynomial
 are the intercepts of its derivative.  Since the derivative of a func
tion at a point represents the slope of the tangent line to the graph \+
of the that function at the point, then the intercepts of the derivati
ve are places where the the tangent lines to the function are flat, i.
e., are horizontal lines.  At such places the graph is neither increas
ing nor decreasing.  Elsewhere the graph must be either increasing or \+
decreasing.  For a polynomial, local extreme values (local maximums or
 local minimums) must occur at the intercepts of the derivative.  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The \+
follwing features are important in analyzing the graph of a polynomial
:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "    \+
 f.   critical points of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "
                      For a polynomial these are the intercepts of the
 derivative of the polynomial" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g. \+
   local maximum points of the graph of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 274 "                      These are points (x,y) o
n the graph of the function for which the y-value is locally the large
st value of the function.  Nearby values on the graph are lower.  For \+
a polynomials the x-value of the point (x,y) must be a critical point \+
of the polynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local min
imum points of the graph of a function y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 276 "                      These are points (x,y) on the grap
h of the function for which the y-value is locally the smallest value \+
of the function.  Nearby values on the graph are higher.  For a polyno
mials the x-value of the point (x,y) must be a critical point of the p
olynomial." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     i.    regions (interv
als) in the domain of the function where the values of the function ar
e increasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       T
hose regions where the graph rises as the graph is traversed from left
 to right.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomia
ls, these regions are bounded by the critical points and may stretch t
o +/- infinity." }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions \+
(intervals) in the domain of the function where the values of the func
tion are decreasing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                 \+
      Those regions where the graph falls as the graph is traversed fr
om left to right.  For a continuous function, and in particular for po
lynomials, these regions are bounded by the critical points and may st
retch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 275 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a g
raph of the polynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally represent \+
the features of the graph.  Include the graph of the deriviative of th
e polynomial on the plot.   Plot the function in red and the derviativ
e in green.   " }{TEXT 269 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomia
l find each of the above ten graphcial characteristics (a.  thru j.):
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " 
